  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks are designed to promote cooperation among countries and establish standards for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities. Some of the key international initiatives include:\n\n### 1. **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental organization established in 1989 to develop policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n   - It sets international standards (known as the **FATF Recommendations**) that countries are encouraged to implement in their legal and regulatory systems.\n   - The FATF also conducts mutual evaluations to assess countries' compliance with these standards.\n\n### 2. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (Vienna Convention): This was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering, specifically in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (Palermo Convention): This convention requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish measures to combat it.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Corruption (2003)** (Merida Convention): This convention includes provisions to prevent and combat money laundering related to corruption.\n\n### 3. **The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee, part of the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), has issued guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering, such as the **1988 Basel Statement of Principles** and subsequent updates.\n\n### 4. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has implemented several Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Directives, which harmonize AML laws across member states. The **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD6)**, effective as of December 2020, strengthens rules on transparency, beneficial ownership, and criminal liability.\n\n### 5. **Wolfsberg Group Principles**\n   - The Wolfsberg Group, an association of global banks, has developed AML principles and guidelines for financial institutions, particularly in areas like correspondent banking and private banking.\n\n### 6. **Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units**\n   - The Egmont Group facilitates international cooperation among Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs) to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### 7. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**\n   - These organizations provide technical assistance and support to countries in implementing AML measures and improving their financial systems.\n\n### Key Principles in International AML Frameworks\n- **Criminalization of Money Laundering**: Countries are required to make money laundering a criminal offense.\n- **Customer Due Diligence (CDD)**: Financial institutions must verify the identity of their customers and monitor transactions.\n- **Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR)**: Institutions must report suspicious transactions to the relevant authorities.\n- **International Cooperation**: Countries are encouraged to share information and assist each other in investigations and prosecutions.\n\nWhile these frameworks provide guidelines, enforcement and implementation depend on individual countries' legal systems and regulatory practices. Non-compliance can result in sanctions, reputational damage, or being placed on the FATF's \"grey list\" or \"black list,\" which can affect a country\u2019s access to global financial systems.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
